'''Karlgeorg Hoefer''' ([[February 6]] [[1914]] – [[October 8]] [[2000]]) was a [[German people|German]] [[calligrapher]] and [[typographer]]. 

Hoefer was born in [[Schlesisch-Drehnow]], now [[:pl:Drzonów|Drzonów]], in [[Silesia]]. He taught [[typography]] at the [[Hochschule für Gestaltung Offenbach]] (until 1970 [[Werkkunstschule]]). He held several calligraphy workshops for calligraphic societies in Los Angeles, San Francisco, [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], Boston, Minneapolis-St. Paul, [[Portland, ME|Portland]] and Washington. In 1987 he founded the [[Schreibwerkstatt-Klingspor Offenbach]] and supported the [[Klingspor-Museum]] in Offenbach am Main.

He designed fonts for [[Linotype]], [[Klingspor]], and [[Ludwig & Mayer]].

Today his most commonly seen font is the [[FE-Schrift]], the standard font for German [[Vehicle registration plate|number plate]]s.

He died in Offenbach in 2000.

